# silverman-blog-linkedin ‚Äî engineering standards

Complements [.cursor/rules/silverman-blog-linkedin-project.mdc](.cursor/rules/silverman-blog-linkedin-project.mdc). Read canonical docs before acting ‚Äî do not embed volatile status here:

- [docs/CURRENT-STATE.md](docs/CURRENT-STATE.md) ‚Äî implemented / validated / manual / deferred
- [docs/CONTEXT-AUTHORITY.md](docs/CONTEXT-AUTHORITY.md) ‚Äî authority hierarchy
- [docs/GLOSSARY.md](docs/GLOSSARY.md) ‚Äî Flow A completion layers, handoff vs publication
- [docs/RUNTIME-STATE.md](docs/RUNTIME-STATE.md) ‚Äî live flags only when operational state matters

This file is **Cursor execution guidance** ‚Äî subordinate to canonical OpenSpec specs, ADRs, and project context. Not normative product authority.

## Canonical context and authority

- Canonical specs (`openspec/specs/`) are normative; `src/` and `tests/` are evidence of real behavior.
- Neither layer silently overrides a discrepancy ‚Äî record in CURRENT-STATE and resolve via a new OpenSpec change.
- Archived changes (`openspec/changes/archive/`) are historical only; never cite as active requirements.
- Before non-trivial work: read CURRENT-STATE, relevant specs, ADRs, and existing code paths.
- Consult `openspec/specs/` for normative behavior; use `tests/` to understand expected contracts.
- Accepted ADRs in `docs/decisions/` bind architectural choices ‚Äî do not contradict without a new change.

## Precise status language

- Never bare "Flow A complete" or "Flow A is complete" ‚Äî name the completion layer (see GLOSSARY).
- `flow_a_complete` = campaign lifecycle metadata only; `distribution_scheduled` ‚âÝ LinkedIn API published.
- Blog handoff (files written to checkout) ‚âÝ site published/live (Git commit + push + Pages deploy).
- LinkedIn implemented ‚âÝ operationally validated; n8n imported ‚âÝ unattended automation.
- Distinguish implemented / tested / deployed / validated / enabled / automatic / manual / incomplete / deferred / unknown.
- When reporting worker capability, cite CURRENT-STATE and specs ‚Äî not assumptions from partial reads.
- Editorial folder states (`ready`, `queued`, `processed`, `error`) have specific meanings in GLOSSARY.

## Inspect before editing

- Read the target file, callers, related specs, and tests before changing code.
- Classify artifacts: canonical, generated, operational, historical.
- Check Git status; match naming, types, imports, and patterns in surrounding code.
- Do not invent paths, endpoints, env vars, or capabilities not in specs or CURRENT-STATE.
- For worker endpoints, read route handlers, service modules, and corresponding spec scenarios together.
- For filesystem changes, trace lifecycle moves in both code and `metadata/campaigns/` contracts.

## Scope and anti-overengineering

- Default: smallest coherent diff satisfying approved OpenSpec requirements.
- No unrelated refactors, speculative abstractions, generic wrappers, or fallbacks hiding invalid state.
- Spec-mandated patterns (adapters, idempotency, auth middleware, lifecycle invariants) are allowed.
- Neighbor issues discovered during work: document as follow-ups; do not expand scope without approval.
- One approved OpenSpec change at a time for implementation ‚Äî do not mix unrelated capabilities.
- If implementation reveals a design flaw, pause and suggest artifact updates rather than improvising.

## Python standards

- Match project Python version and dependency constraints in `pyproject.toml` / `requirements.txt`.
- Type hints on public APIs; use `pathlib.Path` for filesystem paths, not raw strings.
- UTC timestamps at boundaries (`datetime.timezone.utc`); validate inputs at HTTP and filesystem edges.
- Structured errors with actionable messages; no secret values in logs or exceptions.
- Dry-run paths must not mutate production state or write side-effect artifacts.
- Reuse existing modules (`src/` layout) ‚Äî extend functions rather than duplicating logic.
- Prefer explicit enums or constants for lifecycle states already defined in specs or metadata schemas.

## API and worker standards

- n8n ‚Üí worker HTTP only ‚Äî never n8n Execute Command (ADR-0001).
- Auth, validation, idempotency, and dry-run semantics per canonical specs.
- Return structured JSON errors; use appropriate HTTP status codes (4xx validation, 5xx unexpected).
- No secrets in HTTP responses; no hidden Git operations from worker endpoints.
- New routes, Docker changes, or n8n workflows require an approved OpenSpec change.
- Guarded features (e.g. LinkedIn publication) must respect enablement env flags ‚Äî fail closed when disabled.

## Filesystem and lifecycle safety

- Confine reads/writes to approved repo and mount paths; no path traversal.
- Prefer atomic writes; respect folder lifecycle invariants (`blog-posts/`, `linkedin-posts/`, `metadata/`).
- No double moves; no false-success metadata when filesystem state disagrees.
- Campaign traceability via `metadata/campaigns/<campaign-id>.json`.
- Blog post is canonical (ADR-0002); LinkedIn posts are distribution assets ‚Äî preserve that separation.
- Reconciliation endpoints align state without repeating pipeline side effects (see GLOSSARY).

## External integration rules

| Integration | Rules |
|-------------|-------|
| **ComfyUI** | Respect enablement flags; dry-run when specified; no duplicate image generation |
| **DeepSeek** | API keys from env only; no secrets in responses or docs |
| **LinkedIn** | Guarded by `SILVERMAN_LINKEDIN_PUBLICATION_ENABLED`; no duplicate external posts |
| **GitHub Pages** | Worker writes checkout mount; human owns commit/push; handoff ‚âÝ live |
| **n8n** | HTTP orchestration only; import ‚âÝ unattended production |

Treat each integration's enablement flag as authoritative ‚Äî do not bypass guards in code or tests.

## Testing standards

- Behavioral tests over trivial assertions; cover happy path, validation failures, and idempotency.
- Deterministic fixtures; no real external API calls in unit tests (mock ComfyUI, DeepSeek, LinkedIn).
- Mirror spec scenarios in test names and assertions where practical.
- Do not weaken assertions to make tests pass; fix root cause.
- Full pytest required only when executable code changes; docs/rules-only changes may skip.
- Run targeted tests for touched modules before declaring implementation complete.

## Warning and quality discipline

- Zero new warnings attributable to your change; fix root causes before completion.
- Narrow suppressions only with inline explanation tied to a specific line/issue.
- Forbid global disables, broad per-file-ignores, or tool-config changes to hide failures.
- Pre-existing unrelated warnings: report separately; do not fix opportunistically without scope.
- Run `git diff --check` before declaring done.

## Documentation and drift prevention

- Capability, topology, or activation changes: update CURRENT-STATE (and RUNTIME-STATE when live flags change).
- Do not embed volatile inventories in Cursor rules; link canonical docs instead.
- Resolve spec‚Üîimplementation discrepancies via OpenSpec ‚Äî do not silently reinterpret.
- Update CONTEXT-AUTHORITY only when authority hierarchy or document roles change.

## Security and secrets

- Never expose API keys, tokens, passwords, or `.env` values in code, docs, HTTP responses, or commits.
- Stage-time secrets audit on new/modified files before commit approval.
- Redact credentials in logs, error messages, and debug output ‚Äî use env var names only.
- Do not commit `.env`, credentials files, or operator secrets even if gitignored.

## Git discipline

- Stage explicit paths only; never commit unless user explicitly requests.
- Three commit boundaries: (1) implementation, (2) spec sync, (3) archive ‚Äî separate commits.
- No amend unless user requests and conditions are met; never force-push main/master.
- Do not push without explicit user approval.
- Follow repository commit message style from recent `git log` when user requests a commit.

## Deployment and live-operation discipline

- Develop on Mac; deploy Docker on `192.168.0.194` at `/data/silverman-blog-linkedin`.
- Deploy is separate from implementation ‚Äî never assume local changes are live.
- Push, deploy, activation, publication, and live mutation require explicit user approval.
- Controlled operational validation with evidence ‚Äî verify state, not just exit codes.
- Check `BUILD_REVISION` via `/health` or deploy metadata when confirming deployed version.
- Operational smoke scripts (e.g. Flow A worker smoke) confirm diagnostics ‚Äî not unattended production.

## Cursor response behavior

- Inspect vs propose vs implement: match mode to task; stop when blocked rather than guessing.
- OpenSpec before code ‚Äî no application changes without an approved change.
- When unclear, ask; when verification fails, fix or report ‚Äî do not skip gates.
- Post-verify edits make verification stale; re-run `/opsx-verify` before commit.
- Use code citations (`startLine:endLine:filepath`) when referencing existing code.
- Proportional responses ‚Äî simple fixes need brief answers; architecture questions need structure.
- Do not create commits, push, deploy, or modify live server state without explicit user approval.

## OpenSpec lifecycle (approval-gated)

Hyphenated commands only ‚Äî see `.cursor/commands/opsx-*.md`:

```text
/opsx-explore (when needed)
‚Üí /opsx-propose ‚Üí review proposal, design, specs, tasks
‚Üí explicit user approval
‚Üí /opsx-apply ‚Üí implementation
‚Üí /opsx-verify ‚Üí explicit commit approval ‚Üí implementation commit
‚Üí /opsx-sync ‚Üí sync review ‚Üí separate sync commit
‚Üí /opsx-archive ‚Üí archive review ‚Üí separate archive commit
‚Üí explicit push approval ‚Üí explicit deploy approval ‚Üí controlled validation
```

No apply on unapproved proposal. No sync before implementation commit. No archive before sync commit.
Verification stale after any post-verify edit ‚Äî re-run `/opsx-verify` before proceeding.

## Definition of done

- [ ] Approved OpenSpec change scope satisfied
- [ ] Inspect-before-edit followed; conventions matched
- [ ] Tests updated when executable code changed; warnings resolved
- [ ] `/opsx-verify` passed (re-run if post-verify edits)
- [ ] `git diff --check` clean; secrets audit clean
- [ ] Implementation commit (with approval) ‚Üí sync ‚Üí archive (separate commits)
- [ ] CURRENT-STATE updated if capability/topology changed

Completion does not imply deployment, push, or live operational validation.
